    "Edgar V. McKnight": "and the application begins\nwith\nv.\n12. Nashville: Abingdon Press,",
    "Harvey Cox, Henry M. Morris": "Saying, I will declare thy name unto my brethren, etc..] These\n[v_Psa_22_22] words, with the following clause, are cited from (<192222>\nPsalm 22:22) as a\nproof of what the apostle had before asserted; and that this psalm is to be\nunderstood, not of the Jewish nation, or people of Israel, nor of Esther `[char_Esther_Ref]`, nor\nof David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, but of the Messiah, appears from the title of it, \u201cAijeleth,\nShahar\u201d, which signifies \u201cthe morning hind\u201d; from the particular account of\nChrist's sufferings in it; from his several offices herein pointed to; from the\nconversion of the Gentiles it prophesies of; and from several passages cited\n[v_Mat_27_35] from hence, and applied to Christ; (see <402735>Matthew 27:35,39,43,46). And\nthese are the words of Christ addressed to his Father; whose name he\npromises to declare to his brethren; meaning not the Jews, in general, his\nbrethren according to the flesh; but his disciples and followers, particularly\nthe twelve apostles, and the five hundred brethren to whom he appeared\nafter his resurrection; and indeed all the saints and people of God may be\nincluded: and by his name he would declare to them, is not meant any\nparticular name of his, as Elohim, El-shaddai, Jehovah, or the like; but\nrather he himself, and the perfections of his nature, which he, the only\nbegotten Son, lying in his bosom, has declared; though the Gospel seems\n34\n[v_Jhn_17_6] chiefly to be designed; (see <431706>John `[char_John_Ref]` 17:6,26) and this Christ declared with\ngreat exactness and accuracy, with clearness and perspicuity, and with all\nintegrity and fidelity: he spoke it out plainly, and concealed no part of it; as\nhe received it from his Father, he faithfully made it known to his people;\nthis is expressive of Christ's prophetic office, of his preaching of the\nGospel, both in his own person, and by his ministers:\nin the midst of the church will I sing praise unto thee; or \u201ca hymn\u201d; this is\nto be understood not of the church above, but of the church below; and not\nof the synagogue of the Jews, but of the disciples of Christ, and of his\nsinging an hymn to God, with and among them, as he did at the institution\n[v_Mat_26_30] of the supper, (<402630>Matthew 26:30) for though the number of the apostles\nwas but small, yet they made a congregation or church, and which was a\npure and glorious one. With the Jews f32, ten men made a congregation.\nVer.",
    "John Trapp": "I will be merciful ] I will be propitious through Christ, the propitiation for our sins, #1Jo 2:2 . To their unrighteousness, and their sins and iniquities ] All kinds and degrees of sins, #Ex 34:6,7 Mic 7:17 . All sins and blasphemies shall be forgiven to the sons of men #Mt 12:31 . I was a blasphemer, saith Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` (that was a grievous sin against the first table), I was a persecutor (that was a great sin against the second table), yet I obtained mercy; why then should any one despair Will I remember no more ] Nihil oblivisci solet praeter iniurias, saith Cicero of Caesar. He was wont to forget nothing but shrewd turns. And of our Henry VI it is storied that he was of that happy memory that he never forgat anything but injury. (Daniel Contin. by Trussel.) Let us but remember our sins with grief, and God will forget them. Let us see them to confession, and we shall never see them to our confusion. He is a forgiving God, #Ne 9:31 . None like him for that, #Mic 7:18 . He doth it naturally, #Ex 20:6 ; abundantly, #Isa 55:7 ; constantly, #Ps 130:4 Joh 1:27 Mal 3:6 .\nVer.\n12. I will be merciful] I will be propitious through Christ, the propitiation for our sins, #1Jo 2:"
